      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":322,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very easy, let the body wake up. Focus on relaxed breathing and loose shoulders.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":35,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a comfortable aerobic pace. Conversational effort throughout — you should be able to speak in full sentences.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease off the pace for the final 5 minutes. Follow with light dynamic stretching, especially calf and Achilles.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin at the slower end of easy pace (5:56/km) for the first 5 minutes before settling into your comfortable aerobic rhythm.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Slow to a walk for 2 minutes post-run. Perform calf raises and gentle Achilles stretches — given your history of left Achilles tendinitis, keep this a daily habit.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Monday's easy run sets the aerobic tone for the week. At VDOT 46.7, your easy zone (5:22–5:56/km) is wide — err toward the slower end on Mondays after a Sunday long run. This run is about blood flow and recovery, not fitness building. Resist the urge to push.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2Max Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":50,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":251,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2 km easy jog to raise core temperature. Include 4x20-second strides in the final 400m of the warmup to prime the neuromuscular system.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":251,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"5x1 km at interval pace (4:11/km). Each rep should feel hard but controlled — roughly 5K race effort. Maintain good form: tall posture, quick cadence, relaxed hands.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"400m jog recovery between each interval. Keep moving — do not stop. Recovery should feel easy but not too long.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"1.5–2 km easy jog cooldown. Bring heart rate down gradually before stopping.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Thorough warmup is essential before intervals. 2 km easy jog followed by dynamic drills (leg swings, high knees, butt kicks) and 4 short strides at interval pace to prime the legs.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"At least 1.5 km easy jog after the final interval. Do not skip this — it aids lactate clearance. Follow with calf stretches and foam rolling if available.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Tuesday intervals target your VO2max system, the engine that drives your threshold and marathon fitness. At maintenance phase, 5x1 km at 4:11/km is a proven, manageable stimulus. This mirrors your recent training history, so the volume is appropriate. The key is consistency of pace across all 5 reps — if rep 4 or 5 falls off significantly, note it and consider 4 reps next cycle.\",\"perceived_effort\":8},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Recovery Easy Run\",\"target_distance_km\":6,\"target_duration_minutes\":36,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":356,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":356,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":36,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"True recovery run — stay at 5:56/km or slower. Heart rate should stay well below threshold. If you feel flat or heavy from Tuesday's intervals, that is normal and expected.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed — the entire run IS the warmup. Start at a walk for 1–2 minutes if legs feel stiff.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"End with 5 minutes of walking and targeted Achilles/calf stretching. This is a good day for foam rolling the calves and left Achilles area.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Wednesday is a true recovery day in disguise. After hard intervals on Tuesday, your body needs gentle movement to flush metabolic waste and begin repair. Six kilometers at 5:56/km is the prescription — slower is fine, faster is not. Think of this as active recovery, not training. Your Achilles history makes this discipline especially important.\",\"perceived_effort\":2},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Lactate Threshold Tempo Run\",\"target_distance_km\":12,\"target_duration_minutes\":53,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":268,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":11,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2 km easy jog warmup. Gradually build from 5:56 to 5:22/km over the 2 km. Include a few 20-second pickups at the end to prime the legs for threshold effort.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":36,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":268,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"8 km continuous at threshold pace (4:28/km). This is comfortably hard — you can speak a few words but not hold a conversation. Effort should feel like a 10K race pace or slightly easier. Stay relaxed in the face and shoulders.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":11,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2 km easy jog cooldown. Bring the effort down gradually. Do not stop abruptly after threshold work.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"2 km easy jog with gradual pace build. Include dynamic drills if time allows. The warmup is non-negotiable before threshold work — cold muscles at threshold pace invite injury.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"2 km easy jog followed by static stretching (hip flexors, calves, hamstrings). Pay particular attention to left calf and Achilles — gentle eccentric heel drops are beneficial post-run.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Thursday's tempo run is the cornerstone of your maintenance week. Eight kilometers at 4:28/km (your Daniels threshold pace) raises your lactate threshold — the single most important predictor of marathon performance. In a maintenance phase, the goal is to hold the fitness you've built, not push beyond it. Run this at a steady, controlled effort. If conditions are warm or you're fatigued, slow by 5–10 sec/km rather than forcing the pace.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":322,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start easy and loose. Friday follows a hard Thursday — legs may feel heavy. That is fine.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":35,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Comfortable aerobic effort. Stay in the 5:22–5:56/km range. Listen to your body — if you feel genuinely fatigued, slow down or cut to 6 km.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease off the pace. Finish feeling like you could have run further.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start at the easy end of your pace range. Friday is a buffer day between Thursday's tempo and Saturday's rest — keep it genuinely easy.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Light stretching post-run. Prioritize sleep tonight ahead of Sunday's long run.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Friday's easy run maintains aerobic volume without adding meaningful stress. At 55 km per week, you need the volume but not the intensity today. This run should feel almost effortless — if it doesn't, consider whether you need an extra rest day instead. Your body's signals are always more reliable than the plan.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"title\":\"Active Recovery — Cross-Training\",\"target_distance_km\":0,\"target_duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":0,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":0,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":0,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Low-impact cross-training: cycling, swimming, yoga, or elliptical at easy effort. Heart rate should stay below 130 bpm. This is not a fitness day — it is a recovery and mobility day.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup required. Ease into whatever activity you choose over the first 5 minutes.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Finish with 10 minutes of yoga or targeted mobility work. Focus on hip flexors, calves, Achilles, and thoracic spine.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Saturday is a deliberate rest-from-running day. Cross-training keeps blood flowing and maintains the habit of daily movement without adding impact stress to your legs ahead of Sunday's long run. Given your Achilles history, protecting Saturday as a no-run day is a smart long-term investment. Yoga or swimming are ideal choices.\",\"perceived_effort\":2},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Aerobic Long Run\",\"target_distance_km\":20,\"target_duration_minutes\":119,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":356,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":339,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 10 minutes at 5:56/km or slower. Let the body ease into the effort. Do not rush the warmup phase of a long run.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":99,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Maintain easy aerobic pace (5:56/km) throughout. The long run is about time on feet and aerobic adaptation, not pace. If you feel good in the final 5 km, you may pick up slightly toward 5:22/km — but only if it feels genuinely effortless. Fuel every 45 minutes with a gel or equivalent. Hydrate consistently.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 10 minutes at slowest easy pace or walk-jog. Bring the effort down gradually. Do not stop abruptly.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin at 5:56/km or slower for the first 2 km. No strides or pickups before a long run. Let the aerobic system warm up naturally over the first 15–20 minutes.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 5 minutes post-run. Rehydrate and refuel within 30 minutes. Perform gentle stretching — calves, hamstrings, hip flexors. Eccentric heel drops for Achilles health. Elevate legs if possible.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Sunday's long run is the anchor of your training week and the most important session for maintaining your marathon fitness base. At 20 km, this matches your current long run distance — no progression needed in a maintenance phase. Run the full distance at easy pace (5:56/km). The goal is aerobic stimulus and muscular endurance, not speed. Your Chicago Marathon showed the cost of warm conditions — practice fueling and hydration strategies on long runs regardless of weather. Keep total weekly volume around 54–56 km, consistent with your current base.\",\"perceived_effort\":5}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
